column12: Yes, when plans change suddenly, I often feel overwhelmed and panicked. I start thinking about everything that could go wrong and it makes me restless. I don’t have strict routines, but I do feel better when things are predictable. When unexpected things happen, my heart races, and I find it hard to focus or calm down. Even small disruptions sometimes trigger a lot of anxiety for me
column13: When plans change unexpectedly, I start feeling tense and panicked. I usually overthink the new situation and struggle to adjust. I try deep breathing or isolating myself to cope, but it doesn't always help.
column14: Crowded or noisy places right after a change make it worse. I’ve tried journaling and using calming music, which sometimes helps, but avoidance often feels like the easiest option in the moment

column7: Yes, focusing has been really hard lately.
column8: I don’t really have rituals, but I double-check things more when I’m anxious.
column9: Yes, I struggle to explain how I feel sometimes.
column10: Loud places make me anxious, but I don’t avoid them completely.
column11: I get thrown off when my routine changes, but I try to adapt.

column2: I've been feeling very anxious and unsettled, like I constantly have to check or fix things
column3: Yes, I’ve started washing my hands repeatedly and double-checking locks more than usual
column4: I'm constantly worried something bad will happen if I don’t follow certain routines or do things a specific number of times
column5: Not really. I feel embarrassed if I’m caught repeating behaviors like rechecking or arranging things
column6: I stay up late because I need to repeatedly check if I've turned off the stove or locked the doors
column7: Yes, my mind keeps going back to whether I’ve done things correctly or not
column8: Definitely. I have to arrange objects in a certain way or repeat actions until they feel “right."
column9: Yes, it’s hard to talk about my compulsions because I fear people won’t understand.
column10: Not much. My anxiety mostly revolves around order, cleanliness, and fears of harm
column11: Very. If I can’t follow my usual checking routines, I feel extremely uneasy and panicked
column12: Yes, I’ve noticed that my need to check things gets much worse when I feel stressed or uncertain—especially around tasks like locking the door, turning off appliances, or sending emails. I often feel like if I don’t repeat these actions several times, something bad might happen. It’s not just a habit—it feels like an urgent need.  I haven’t spoken with a professional yet, mostly because I wasn’t sure if this was something serious, but it’s been affecting my daily routine and peace of mind for quite some time now
column13: Thank you for sharing your experiences with me. To help clarify your symptoms and better understand what you're going through, could you tell me if you have noticed any difficulties in social interactions or communication, any specific repetitive behaviors or interests that significantly occupy your time, or any sensitivity to sensory input, such as lights, sounds, or textures? These can also be important aspects to consider alongside the anxiety and compulsive behaviors you've described
column14: I don’t usually have issues communicating or interacting with others, but I do find myself caught in repetitive behaviors like checking and organizing things a certain way. For example, I often need to tap objects or repeat phrases in my head to ease anxiety. These routines can take up a significant part of my day.  As for sensory input, I can get slightly overwhelmed by loud or sudden noises, but it’s mostly my thoughts and compulsions that drive my stress. I spend a lot of time trying to neutralize the “what if” thoughts that won’t go away unless I do something specific
